Police participated in efforts to ensure the safety of the community at the weekend, when they made the arrest. Officers also followed up on information they received from the community about dagga being sold at an address. “Upon their arrival they found a big paper bag containing dagga which was valued at a substantial amount. “A 48-year-old man was arrested for possession of dagga,” said police spokeswoman Noloyiso Rwexana. The man died on the scene due to his injuries, said the police. The suspect is expected to appear in the Worcester Magistrate's Court on a charge of murder. Meanwhile, officers arrested a 21-year-old man in Simpson Street in Riverview, Worcester, after he tried to evade arrest. He was observed by officers carrying a suspicious-looking bag. Police spokesperson Noloyiso Rwexana said: “Police searched the bag and a total of 1 032 mandrax tablets and 180 packets of tik were found. “The estimated street value of the drugs is R65 000.”